Sex determination in dioecious plants can be environmentally or genetically controlled (
 Korpelainen 1998). The genetic control of sex determination in plants ranges from few individual genes (
 Spigler et al. 2008; 
 Akagi et al. 2014) to non-recombining heteromorphic sex chromosomes (
 Sakamoto et al. 1998; 
 Sousa, Fuchs, and Renner 2013). Most heteromorphic systems are XY male and XX female, but female-specific sex chromosomes (ZW) also exist, for example, in 
 Silene and 
 Salix (
 Slancarova et al. 2013; 
 Pucholt, Rönnberg-Wästljung, and Berlin 2015). Although the genetic control of dioecy has been studied in several species, the determination of sex and the evolutionary forces driving sexual dimorphism are not well understood.
